export const story = {"seriesId":"the-eastern-valleys","storyId":"the-eastern-valleys","storyKey":"the-eastern-valleys/the-eastern-valleys","seriesTitle":"The Eastern Valleys","seriesDescription":"When the letter finally arrives, the Aldridge family leaves their city apartment for forty hectares of newly terraformed land. Through Oliver's eyes, we follow a year of building, planting, and discovering what it means to make a home from nothing—with hard work, good neighbors, and two faithful robots.","title":"The Eastern Valleys","author":"Andrew","description":"When the letter finally arrives, the Aldridge family leaves their city apartment for forty hectares of newly terraformed land. Through Oliver's eyes, we follow a year of building, planting, and discovering what it means to make a home from nothing—with hard work, good neighbors, and two faithful robots.","ageRange":"8-10","genre":"Science Fiction","tags":["frontier","family","robots","homesteading","community","future","inspiring"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"Forty Hectares","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# Forty Hectares\n\nThe letter came on a Tuesday.\n\nPapa held it up for Mama to see, and Mama put her hand over her mouth the way she did when something was too big for words. Oliver knew what it meant before anyone told him. Three years they had waited. Three years of Papa checking the network every morning, hoping their name would come up on the settlement list.\n\n\"Forty hectares,\" Papa said. \"In the eastern valleys. Ours.\"\n\nThea looked up from where she was building a tower out of blocks. \"What's a hector?\"\n\n\"Hectare,\" Oliver said. He had looked it up once, after Papa first put their name on the list. \"It's a piece of land. A hundred meters by a hundred meters. And we're getting forty of them.\"\n\nThea knocked over her tower. \"Is that big?\"\n\n\"It's bigger than anything we've ever had,\" Papa said.\n\nOliver tried to imagine it. Their apartment had three rooms—a kitchen, a bedroom for Mama and Papa, and a smaller room he shared with Thea. The hallway outside their door was twelve meters long. He had measured it once, walking heel to toe. A hundred meters was more than eight of those hallways. And they were getting forty squares that size.\n\n\"When do we go?\" Thea asked. She was already up, pulling at Papa's sleeve.\n\nPapa looked at Mama. Mama looked back at him. Something passed between them that Oliver didn't quite understand—something about being scared and excited at the same time.\n\n\"Soon,\" Papa said. \"Before the planting season starts. We'll need time to build.\"\n\n---\n\nThat night, Papa showed them the survey images on the kitchen screen. Oliver pulled his chair close and studied them carefully.\n\nThe land was brown and flat, stretching toward green hills in the distance. A river ran along one edge, silver and winding. There were no buildings, no roads, no other people—just the land and the sky and tiny marker stakes showing where their property began and ended.\n\n\"The terraforming crews finished last spring,\" Papa explained. \"The soil's been treated. The air's been balanced. Everything's ready for families to come and build.\"\n\n\"Where will our house be?\" Oliver asked.\n\nPapa pointed to a spot near the river. \"I'm thinking here. Close to water, with good drainage. We'll have the fields behind us, and room to expand if we need to.\"\n\n\"I want a window that faces the river,\" Thea said.\n\n\"You can have any window you want,\" Papa told her. \"We're building this house ourselves. We get to decide everything.\"\n\nOliver stared at the image. It was hard to believe that flat brown rectangle would become their home. Right now it was just dirt and stakes and possibility.\n\n---\n\nThe next weeks were full of work. Papa sold their furniture—they couldn't take it in the crawler, and besides, Papa said he would build new furniture when they got there. Mama sorted through their clothes and belongings, deciding what to keep and what to leave behind.\n\n\"You can each bring one box of things,\" Mama told Oliver and Thea. \"Choose carefully.\"\n\nOliver thought about this for a long time. His room was small, but it was full of things he cared about. His books, his rock collection, the model crawler he had built from a kit, the drawings he had made of plants and animals from his schoolwork.\n\nIn the end, he packed his three favorite books, his best rocks, a small notebook and two pencils, and a photograph of their family taken when he was five and Thea was two. The model crawler wouldn't fit, so he took it apart carefully and saved only the wheels—Papa might need spare parts.\n\nThea's box was easier. She filled it with her dolls and a blanket and a small music player that had belonged to Grandmother.\n\n---\n\nThe crawler arrived on a gray morning two weeks before they were scheduled to leave. A man drove it to their building and handed Papa the keys.\n\n\"She's old,\" the man said, \"but she runs well. Good luck out there.\"\n\nOliver followed Papa outside to look at it. The crawler was big—bigger than their apartment, with six heavy wheels and a canvas cover stretched over the back. The sides were dented and scratched from years of use, but the wheels looked solid and the engine hummed steadily when Papa started it.\n\n\"This will be our home for the journey,\" Papa said. \"Six hundred kilometers. About two weeks if the weather holds.\"\n\nOliver walked around the crawler slowly, looking at everything. There were storage compartments built into the sides, a solar array folded on top, and a small step-ladder leading up to the covered back where they would sleep.\n\n\"Can I go inside?\" he asked.\n\n\"Go ahead.\"\n\nOliver climbed the step-ladder and pushed through the canvas flap. Inside, the crawler was dim and smelled like old canvas and machine oil. There were benches along both sides that folded down into beds, hooks for hanging things, and small windows cut into the canvas walls. It wasn't pretty, but it was solid and practical.\n\nHe sat on one of the benches and tried to imagine living here for two weeks. Eating here. Sleeping here. Watching the world change outside those small windows as they traveled toward their new home.\n\n---\n\nThe robots came out of storage the day before they left.\n\nMarchman was big. Taller than Papa, broader than the doorway. He had to duck and turn sideways to fit into their apartment. His body was gray metal, scratched and worn from years of work. He had four arms—two heavy ones for lifting and two smaller ones for fine work—and a flat, patient face with simple sensor lights where eyes would be.\n\nPapa had owned Marchman for twelve years, since before Oliver was born. Marchman had helped Papa with his maintenance work in the city, lifting heavy machinery, holding things steady, doing the jobs that were too hard or too dangerous for a person alone.\n\nMarchman didn't speak. He didn't need to. He listened to instructions and he worked. That was what he was built for.\n\nPenny was different.\n\nShe was smaller than Marchman, about Mama's height, with a rounder body and clever hands that had dozens of tiny tools folded into them. Her face was more expressive than Marchman's—she could tilt her head, raise her sensor plates like eyebrows, move in ways that felt almost human.\n\nPenny had belonged to Mama's family. She had been there when Mama was a girl, helping in the kitchen, mending clothes, teaching Mama how to bake bread and preserve food and fix things that broke.\n\n\"Penny taught me everything I know about keeping a house,\" Mama told Oliver once. \"She's patient. She explains things well. She never gets frustrated when you make mistakes.\"\n\nNow Penny stood in their small kitchen, her head tilted slightly as she looked around at the boxes and bags and empty spaces where furniture used to be.\n\n\"It will be good to have land again,\" Mama said to her quietly. \"Real soil. Real sunlight. Not just grow-lights and hydroponics.\"\n\nPenny hummed softly. It was a sound she made when she was thinking, or when she agreed with something. Oliver had heard that hum all his life. It was a comforting sound.\n\n---\n\nThe morning they left, Oliver woke before dawn.\n\nHe lay in his bunk and listened to the quiet sounds of the apartment—Thea breathing below him, the soft whir of the air recycler, the distant rumble of the city outside. He had slept in this room for nine years. He knew every crack in the ceiling, every squeak of the floor, every way the light came through the window at different times of day.\n\nAfter today, he would never sleep here again.\n\nHe got up quietly and walked through the apartment. It looked strange now—empty and echoing, the walls bare, the floors scuffed where furniture used to sit. It didn't look like home anymore. It looked like a place where someone used to live.\n\nPapa found him standing in the kitchen.\n\n\"Nervous?\" Papa asked.\n\nOliver nodded.\n\nPapa put his hand on Oliver's shoulder. \"That's all right. I'm nervous too. Your mother is nervous. But we wanted this, Oliver. We've been waiting for this. And we're going to build something good out there. Something that's ours.\"\n\n\"What if it's too hard?\"\n\n\"It will be hard,\" Papa said. \"But hard isn't the same as bad. Hard just means it matters. The things worth having are usually hard to get.\"\n\n---\n\nThey loaded the last boxes into the crawler as the sun came up. Marchman lifted the heavy crates—seeds, tools, the water recycler, bolts of cloth, the solar panels they would need for the house. Penny packed the smaller things carefully, making sure nothing would shift or break during the journey.\n\nNeighbors came out to watch. Some of them waved. A few came to say goodbye and wish them luck. Oliver didn't know most of them well—in the city, people lived close together but didn't always know each other.\n\nFinally, everything was loaded. Papa climbed into the driver's seat. Mama sat beside him. Oliver and Thea climbed into the back, finding spots on the benches among the boxes and bags.\n\nMarchman and Penny would walk alongside the crawler. They didn't need to ride—they didn't get tired the way people did. And walking saved power in the crawler's batteries, power they might need later.\n\n\"Everyone ready?\" Papa called back.\n\n\"Ready!\" Thea shouted.\n\nOliver just nodded. His throat felt tight.\n\nPapa started the engine. The crawler hummed and vibrated. Slowly, it began to roll forward.\n\nOliver looked out the small back window as they pulled away. He watched their building get smaller. He watched the familiar streets slide past. He watched the city that had been his whole world begin to disappear behind them.\n\nFor a moment, he wanted to call out, to tell Papa to stop, to say he had changed his mind. This was too big, too scary, too much.\n\nBut then he remembered what Papa had said. Hard isn't the same as bad.\n\nHe turned around and faced forward, looking through the canvas flap at the road ahead. Somewhere out there, six hundred kilometers away, forty hectares were waiting.\n\nHe didn't look back again.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"The Long Road","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# The Long Road\n\nThe first day, they passed through the outer districts of the city.\n\nOliver watched through the canvas window as familiar things gave way to unfamiliar ones. First the tall apartment buildings, crowded together like people waiting for a train. Then the lower industrial buildings, with their chimneys and loading docks. Then the agricultural domes, great curved structures where food was grown under artificial light.\n\nAnd then, around midday, the city ended.\n\nOliver had never seen the edge before. He had known it existed—the city had to end somewhere—but he had never actually watched it happen. One moment there were buildings and roads and people. The next moment there was just... land.\n\nOpen land, stretching in every direction, covered with low scrubby plants he didn't recognize. The sky seemed bigger out here. The horizon seemed farther away.\n\n\"This is the settled zone,\" Papa called back to them. \"Terraformed about fifty years ago. Some families farm here, but most of the land is still wild.\"\n\nThea pressed her face against the window. \"Where are the animals?\"\n\n\"They're out there,\" Papa said. \"They just know how to hide. Maybe you'll see some tonight, when it's quiet.\"\n\n---\n\nThat first evening, Papa stopped the crawler beside a small stream.\n\n\"This is where we'll camp,\" he said. \"Everyone out. There's work to do.\"\n\nOliver had never set up a camp before. In the city, everything was already there—walls, floors, beds, kitchens. You didn't have to make anything. You just used what was built.\n\nOut here, everything had to be done.\n\nPapa showed him how to unfold the solar shade from the top of the crawler, stretching it out to cover a space where they could sit and cook. Mama started a small cookfire using dried fuel bricks from their supplies. Marchman unloaded the water canisters and carried them to the stream to fill.\n\n\"Can I help?\" Oliver asked Penny.\n\nPenny tilted her head—that way she had of looking at you when she was thinking. Then she handed him a bundle of stakes and rope.\n\n\"The perimeter alarm,\" she said. Her voice was soft and slightly mechanical, but warm somehow. \"We set it around our camp each night. It will beep if anything large crosses it.\"\n\nOliver followed her instructions carefully. He walked in a wide circle around the crawler, pushing stakes into the ground at regular intervals, running the thin alarm wire between them. It wasn't hard work, but it was real work. It mattered.\n\nWhen he finished, Penny checked his work and adjusted two of the stakes.\n\n\"Good,\" she said. \"Tomorrow, you'll remember which ones to move.\"\n\n---\n\nThey ate supper as the sun went down.\n\nMama had made a simple meal—rehydrated stew with bread from their supplies. It wasn't fancy, but Oliver was hungry, and the food tasted better than he expected. Maybe food always tasted better when you'd worked for it.\n\nAfter supper, Papa took out his concertina.\n\nIt was an old instrument, smaller than a guitar, with buttons instead of keys and bellows that wheezed when you squeezed them. Papa had owned it since he was young. He said it was the one thing he had brought from his parents' house when he left to start his own life.\n\nPapa played a slow song that Oliver didn't recognize—something about rivers and traveling and coming home. The music floated out over the empty land, the only sound except for insects chirping in the grass.\n\nWhen the song ended, Thea was asleep against Mama's shoulder. Mama carried her into the crawler and put her to bed.\n\nOliver stayed outside with Papa.\n\n\"Look up,\" Papa said quietly.\n\nOliver looked.\n\nThe sky was full of stars.\n\nNot a few stars, not the scattered handful he had seen from the city where the lights drowned out most of the sky. Hundreds of stars. Thousands of them. More stars than Oliver had ever imagined could exist.\n\nA thick band of light stretched across the middle of the sky—the galaxy itself, Papa said, seen from the inside. And there, rising over the eastern hills, were the two moons. One pale blue, one amber, hanging in the darkness like lanterns.\n\n\"I never knew,\" Oliver whispered.\n\n\"Neither did I, the first time I saw it,\" Papa said. \"I was about your age. My father brought me out past the city one night, just to see the stars. I never forgot it.\"\n\nOliver stared until his neck hurt. He tried to count the stars, but there were too many. He tried to find patterns in them, shapes and lines, but the patterns kept shifting the longer he looked.\n\nFinally, Papa said it was time for bed.\n\nOliver climbed into the crawler and found his bunk. But before he slept, he reached into his box of belongings and pulled out his notebook. By the dim light from the window, he wrote:\n\n*Day 1. Left the city. Camped by a stream. More stars than I could count.*\n\nThen he added one more line:\n\n*Tomorrow I will find a stone to remember this place.*\n\n---\n\nThe days that followed blurred together.\n\nEach morning, Oliver woke before dawn to help break camp. He learned to take down the perimeter alarm, coil the rope properly, pack the stakes so they wouldn't rattle. He learned to check the crawler's water reserves and battery levels. He learned which boxes held food and which held tools and where everything belonged.\n\nEach day, the crawler rolled forward across the land. The terrain changed slowly—scrubby plains giving way to grassland, grassland giving way to gentle hills covered with purple-gray plants Oliver had never seen in any book.\n\n\"Native species,\" Mama explained. \"The terraforming helped some Earth plants grow, but the planet's own life is starting to come back too. Scientists think it was here millions of years ago, before the climate changed. Now the soil is right for it again.\"\n\nThea had a thousand questions. Why was the sky that color? What were those plants called? Why did Marchman's joints squeak sometimes? How far was it to the eastern valleys? Were there really animals out here? What did they eat? Why didn't they live in the city too?\n\nMama and Papa answered as many questions as they could. When they didn't know the answer, they said so.\n\n\"We're all learning,\" Papa told her. \"That's part of why we're going. To learn what this land can teach us.\"\n\n---\n\nEach evening, they stopped to camp.\n\nOliver kept his promise to himself. At every campsite, he found a stone—something interesting, something different from the stones at the last place. A smooth gray pebble from the first stream. A red-speckled rock from the grasslands. A flat blue stone from a dry creek bed in the hills.\n\nHe kept them in a small pouch, arranged in order. When he looked at them, he could remember each place, each night, each step of the journey.\n\n\"You're building a collection,\" Penny observed one evening, watching him sort through his stones.\n\n\"I want to remember,\" Oliver said. \"I want to know where we've been.\"\n\nPenny's sensor plates lifted slightly—her version of a smile. \"That's a good instinct. The past helps us understand the present.\"\n\n---\n\nOn the eighth night, they camped on a high ridge overlooking a vast valley.\n\nThe sun was setting, painting the sky in shades of orange and pink. Below them, the valley stretched for miles, covered in tall golden grass that rippled in the wind like water.\n\n\"Look,\" Papa said, pointing toward the far edge of the valley. \"See that silver line? That's the Glass River. And beyond it—those green hills—that's the eastern valleys.\"\n\nOliver's heart jumped. \"That's where we're going?\"\n\n\"That's where we're going. A few more days, and we'll be there.\"\n\nOliver stared at the distant hills. They looked far away still, but closer than anything had looked before. Real. Possible.\n\nSomewhere in those hills, forty hectares were waiting.\n\nHe reached down and picked up a stone from the ridge—pale white, shaped like a teardrop. He would add it to his collection tonight. The last stone of the journey, before everything changed.\n\n---\n\nThat night, lying in his bunk, Oliver listened to the wind outside the crawler.\n\nIt was a different sound than the wind in the city, which had always been broken up by buildings and machines. Out here, the wind moved freely. It came from somewhere far away and was going somewhere far away, and they were just passing through.\n\nHe thought about the city, about his old apartment, about the room he had shared with Thea and the hallway he had measured with his feet. All of that felt distant now, like something from a long time ago.\n\nThis journey was changing him. He could feel it. Each day of work, each stone he collected, each night under the stars—they were all making him into someone different. Someone who knew how to set up camp and read the landscape and understand that the world was bigger than he had ever imagined.\n\nHe wasn't sure yet who that person would be.\n\nBut he was ready to find out.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Glass River","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Glass River\n\nThey reached the river on the eleventh day.\n\nOliver saw it first—a flash of silver through the trees ahead, catching the morning light. As they drew closer, the flash became a ribbon, and the ribbon became a river, wide and slow and impossibly clear.\n\n\"That's why they call it the Glass River,\" Papa said, stopping the crawler on a low rise above the bank. \"You can see all the way to the bottom.\"\n\nOliver climbed out and walked to the edge. Papa was right. The water was so clear it almost wasn't there. He could see smooth stones on the riverbed, ten feet down. He could see small fish darting in the current, silver and quick. He could see the ripples in the sand where the water flowed over it.\n\n\"It's beautiful,\" Mama said quietly.\n\nIt was. But it was also wide. Very wide. And somewhere on the other side was their land.\n\n\"How do we get across?\" Thea asked.\n\nPapa studied the river, shading his eyes with his hand. \"There should be a ford about two kilometers upstream. The maps show a place where the river spreads out and gets shallow. We can cross there.\"\n\n\"Should be?\" Mama said.\n\n\"The maps are from the survey crews. They're a few years old. Rivers change.\" Papa looked at Penny. \"Can you scout ahead? Find the best crossing?\"\n\nPenny nodded once. She walked down the bank, tested the edge of the water with one foot, then stepped in and waded forward. The water came up to her waist, then her chest, and then she was walking on the bottom, completely submerged, following the riverbed upstream.\n\n\"She'll be all right,\" Mama said, seeing Oliver's face. \"Penny doesn't need to breathe like we do. The water won't hurt her.\"\n\nOliver knew that. But it was still strange to watch her disappear under the silver surface, leaving only bubbles behind.\n\n---\n\nThey waited.\n\nPapa walked along the bank, looking for any sign of other crossings. Mama unpacked a midday meal. Thea found a stick and poked at the water, trying to get the fish to come closer.\n\nOliver sat on a rock and watched the river.\n\nIt was peaceful here. The water made a soft rushing sound as it flowed past. Birds called from the trees on the far bank. The air smelled different than it had in the grasslands—wetter, greener, full of growing things.\n\nThis was the edge of their new life. On this side of the river, they were still travelers. On the other side, they would be home.\n\nIf they could get across.\n\nAn hour later, Penny emerged from the water upstream. She walked back to them, water streaming off her metal body, and reported what she had found.\n\n\"The ford is there,\" she said, pointing. \"One point six kilometers. The water spreads wide and becomes shallow—less than one meter deep in most places. But the ground is soft. The crawler may have difficulty.\"\n\n\"May?\" Papa asked.\n\n\"The soil is sandy. It has been raining upstream. There are tracks in the mud—another crawler crossed recently, perhaps a week ago. They made it through, but they left deep ruts.\"\n\nPapa thought about this. \"We'll have to try. Going around would add days, and we're low on supplies.\"\n\n\"I can help,\" Marchman said. It was the first time Oliver had heard him speak on the whole journey. His voice was deep and mechanical, like stones grinding together. \"If the crawler gets stuck, I can pull.\"\n\nPapa nodded. \"Then we try.\"\n\n---\n\nThe ford was exactly where Penny had said it would be.\n\nThe river spread out here, becoming wide and shallow, more like a lake than a stream. Oliver could see the bottom clearly—packed sand with patches of mud, and the deep ruts Penny had mentioned, filled with dark water.\n\nPapa drove the crawler slowly down the bank and into the river.\n\nAt first, everything went well. The wheels found traction on the sandy bottom. Water rose to the wheel hubs, then higher, swirling around the crawler's undercarriage. Oliver and Thea watched from the back, looking down at the clear water flowing past.\n\n\"We're doing it,\" Thea said. \"We're—\"\n\nThe crawler lurched.\n\nThe front left wheel had found soft ground. It sank, tilting the whole vehicle to one side. Papa pressed the accelerator, and the wheels spun, throwing up clouds of muddy water.\n\n\"Hold on,\" Papa said. His voice was calm but tight.\n\nHe tried again. The wheels spun. The crawler sank deeper.\n\n\"We're stuck,\" Mama said.\n\nPapa climbed out of the driver's seat and dropped into the water. It came up to his waist. He waded to the front of the crawler and knelt down, feeling around the sunken wheel with his hands.\n\n\"The sand is like soup,\" he reported. \"The harder we push, the deeper we go.\"\n\nOliver felt his stomach drop. They were stuck in the middle of a river, with all their supplies, with everything they owned. If they couldn't get out—\n\n\"Marchman,\" Papa called.\n\nMarchman was already moving. He waded past Papa to the front of the crawler, his heavy body making waves in the shallow water. He bent down and gripped the front axle with his four arms.\n\n\"When I lift,\" he said, \"drive forward.\"\n\nPapa climbed back into the driver's seat. Mama came to stand beside Oliver and Thea, her hands on their shoulders.\n\n\"Ready?\" Marchman asked.\n\n\"Ready.\"\n\nMarchman pulled.\n\nOliver had never seen anything like it. Marchman's arms strained, his joints creaking with the effort. Slowly, impossibly, the front of the crawler began to rise. The sunken wheel came free of the mud with a wet sucking sound.\n\n\"Now!\" Marchman shouted.\n\nPapa hit the accelerator. The wheels caught. The crawler lurched forward. For a terrible moment Oliver thought they would sink again, but then the wheels found solid ground and they were moving, really moving, climbing out of the soft patch and up the far bank.\n\nThey had made it.\n\n---\n\nPapa stopped the crawler on solid ground and everyone climbed out.\n\nMarchman stood in the shallows, water streaming from his body. Oliver thought he looked tired, which was strange because robots didn't get tired. But something in the way he stood, the way his arms hung at his sides, suggested that the effort had cost him something.\n\n\"Thank you,\" Papa said to him.\n\nMarchman nodded once. \"The crawler is heavy. But not too heavy.\"\n\nPenny went to him and began checking his joints, looking for damage. Oliver heard them talking quietly—Penny's soft voice, Marchman's rumbling one—and he understood that in their own way, they were family too.\n\n---\n\nThey made camp on the far bank that night, even though the sun was still high.\n\n\"We all need rest,\" Papa said. \"Tomorrow we'll reach our land. Tonight, we recover.\"\n\nOliver helped set up camp, going through the familiar motions without thinking. Perimeter alarm. Solar shade. Water canisters. Each task felt different now, on this side of the river. More real somehow.\n\nAfter supper, he walked to the top of a small hill behind the camp. He wanted to see what was ahead.\n\nThe land rose gently before him, rolling hills covered in grass and scattered trees. In the distance, he could see higher hills, green and forested. And somewhere beyond those hills, hidden from view, was the piece of ground that would become their home.\n\nThey were so close now. One more day, maybe two.\n\nHe thought about the journey—the city falling away behind them, the nights under the stars, the stones he had collected at each campsite. He thought about Marchman lifting the crawler out of the river, Penny scouting the ford, Mama staying calm when things went wrong.\n\nThey had done this together. All of them.\n\nHe went back to camp and found his notebook.\n\n*Day 11. Crossed the Glass River. Marchman saved us. Tomorrow we see our land.*\n\n---\n\nThe next morning, they started early.\n\nThe road—if you could call it a road, more like wheel-tracks through the grass—wound up into the green hills. The crawler climbed steadily, the engine humming with the effort.\n\nOliver sat in the front with Papa, watching the landscape unfold. Everything was greener here, more alive. He saw birds he didn't recognize, and once, in the distance, something large and four-legged that disappeared into the trees before he could get a good look.\n\n\"Almost there,\" Papa said.\n\nThey crested a final hill, and Papa stopped the crawler.\n\nBelow them spread a valley, wide and flat and brown. The Glass River curved along one edge, silver in the morning light. Green hills rose on the far side. And in the middle of the valley, barely visible in the grass, were the small white stakes that marked the boundaries of their land.\n\nForty hectares. Four thousand meters on a side.\n\nMore land than Oliver could walk across in an hour. More land than he had ever seen that belonged to anyone, let alone to his family.\n\n\"There it is,\" Papa said quietly. \"That's ours.\"\n\nOliver stared. He tried to take it all in—the size of it, the realness of it, the fact that they had actually made it here. After three years of waiting, after six hundred kilometers of traveling, after everything—\n\nThis was their home.\n\nThea squeezed between them to look. \"It's so big,\" she whispered.\n\n\"Yes,\" Mama said, coming to stand behind them. \"It is.\"\n\nFor a long moment, no one said anything else. They just looked.\n\nThen Papa started the crawler again, and they drove down into the valley, toward the stakes and the brown earth and the beginning of everything new.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Stakes in the Ground","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Stakes in the Ground\n\nThe first night on their land, they slept in the crawler.\n\nIt felt strange. They had slept in the crawler every night for two weeks, but this was different. This time, the ground beneath the wheels was theirs. This time, when Oliver looked out the window, he wasn't looking at a campsite they would leave in the morning. He was looking at home.\n\nHe woke before dawn and lay still, listening.\n\nThe sounds were different here. No city noise, no machine hum from distant factories. Just wind in the grass, insects chirping, and somewhere far off, a bird calling a song he didn't recognize.\n\nHe climbed out of his bunk quietly, not wanting to wake Thea, and pushed through the canvas flap into the cool morning air.\n\nThe sky was turning pink at the edges. Mist hung low over the valley, making everything soft and dreamlike. Oliver could see the river in the distance, a silver ribbon through the fog. He could see the hills rising on the far side, dark shapes against the brightening sky.\n\nAnd he could see the land. Their land. Stretching out in every direction, waiting for them.\n\n---\n\nAfter breakfast, Papa gathered everyone together.\n\n\"Today we survey,\" he said. \"We need to understand exactly what we have. The maps are helpful, but maps don't tell you everything. We need to walk the ground ourselves.\"\n\nThey split up. Mama and Thea would inventory their supplies and organize the crawler for an extended stay. Penny would begin testing the soil in different areas—checking for nutrients, drainage, anything that might affect where they built and planted.\n\nPapa, Oliver, and Marchman would walk the property boundaries.\n\n\"Four hundred meters on each side,\" Papa said, checking the survey documents on his handpad. \"We'll follow the stakes. It'll take most of the morning.\"\n\nOliver had walked four hundred meters before. It was the distance from their apartment building to the market square in the city—a ten-minute walk, nothing special.\n\nBut that was on pavement, in straight lines, with buildings blocking the view. Out here, four hundred meters felt different. The land rolled and dipped. There were no straight lines. And when you could see everything, distances played tricks on you.\n\n---\n\nThey found the first stake at the corner of their property.\n\nIt was a simple metal post, about knee-high, with a number stamped into the top. The survey crews had placed these markers years ago, when they first mapped out the parcels for settlement. They marked where one family's land ended and another's began.\n\nPapa knelt and brushed dirt away from the base. \"Still solid,\" he said. \"Good. We'll need to put in permanent markers eventually, but these will do for now.\"\n\nThey walked along the northern boundary, following the line of stakes. Marchman carried the equipment—a surveyor's rod, a measuring tape, a small device for checking elevation. Oliver's job was to write down the numbers Papa called out.\n\n\"Seventeen meters,\" Papa said, sighting along the rod. \"Slope grade two percent. Ground cover mixed grass and native shrub.\"\n\nOliver wrote it all in his notebook. He wasn't sure what all the numbers meant yet, but Papa said understanding the land was the first step to working it.\n\nThe walking was harder than Oliver expected. The grass was knee-high in places, hiding rocks and holes. His legs ached. His boots got wet from morning dew. But every time he looked up and saw the land stretching out around them—their land—he forgot about being tired.\n\n---\n\nAt the eastern corner, they stopped to rest.\n\nFrom here, Oliver could see the Glass River clearly. It curved along the edge of their property, sparkling in the sunlight. He could see the far bank where they had camped, and beyond it, the path they had taken through the hills.\n\n\"The river's our eastern boundary,\" Papa explained. \"Natural borders are good. They don't move, and everyone knows where they are.\"\n\n\"What about the other sides?\" Oliver asked.\n\n\"Stakes and agreements. Eventually there will be neighbors on all sides, and we'll put in fences or hedges or walls. For now, it's just us.\"\n\nOliver looked west, where their land continued toward the green hills. Somewhere out there, beyond the hills, were other valleys, other settlers, other families starting their own lives. But right now, looking at the empty grass, it felt like they were the only people in the world.\n\n---\n\nThe southern boundary followed a slight ridge.\n\nPapa said the ridge was good for building. Water would drain away instead of pooling. The ground was solid underneath. They could see the whole property from up here.\n\n\"This is where the house will go,\" Papa decided. \"Close to the river for water, up on the ridge for drainage, facing east to catch the morning sun.\"\n\nHe paced out a rectangle in the grass—eight meters by twelve meters. Not big, but enough for a family of four. Room to grow later if they needed it.\n\n\"This is the kitchen,\" Papa said, pointing. \"This is the main room. Back here, bedrooms. And over here\"—he walked to the corner closest to the river—\"a covered porch where we can sit in the evenings and watch the sunset.\"\n\nOliver tried to see it. Right now there was just grass and dirt and sky. But Papa saw something more. Papa saw walls and windows and a place where they would live.\n\n\"When do we start building?\" Oliver asked.\n\n\"Tomorrow. Today, we mark the corners. Then we dig the foundation.\"\n\n---\n\nThat afternoon, Papa showed Oliver how to set a proper stake.\n\n\"The survey stakes are just markers,\" Papa explained. \"They tell you where the boundaries are. Building stakes are different. They tell you exactly where every wall will go. They have to be precise.\"\n\nHe handed Oliver a heavy wooden stake, sharpened to a point at one end. It was heavier than it looked.\n\n\"The corner stakes are the most important,\" Papa said. \"Everything else is measured from them. If the corners are wrong, the whole house will be wrong.\"\n\nMarchman had already dug the first hole—a narrow shaft about half a meter deep, punched straight down through the grass and into the brown soil beneath. Papa set the stake in the hole and held it steady.\n\n\"Check that it's straight,\" he told Oliver.\n\nOliver stepped back and looked. The stake tilted slightly to the left. He told Papa, and Papa adjusted it.\n\n\"Now check from the other direction.\"\n\nOliver walked around to the other side. Straight. He nodded.\n\n\"Good. Now we pack the soil around it.\"\n\nThey worked together, filling the hole with dirt and tamping it down tight. When they finished, the stake stood solid and true, marking the spot where the northeast corner of their house would be.\n\nPapa looked at Oliver. \"Want to do the next one yourself?\"\n\nOliver's heart jumped. \"Really?\"\n\n\"Really. I'll tell you if you're doing it wrong. But I think you're ready.\"\n\n---\n\nThe second stake was harder.\n\nOliver's arms shook holding it in place. The hole wasn't quite straight, so he had to adjust the stake angle to compensate. Twice Papa told him to check his measurements again. Once he packed the soil too loosely and had to start over.\n\nBut finally, finally, the stake was set. Solid. Straight. True.\n\nPapa checked it from every angle. He used the measuring tape to verify the distance from the first stake. He sighted along the line with the surveyor's rod.\n\n\"Perfect,\" he said.\n\nOliver looked at the stake. It was just a piece of wood stuck in the ground. But it was his piece of wood, his stake, the corner of the house he was going to live in.\n\nHe had helped build something. Something real.\n\n---\n\nThat evening, Mama made supper over a fire while Papa and Marchman set the other two corner stakes.\n\nOliver sat by the fire and watched the flames. He was exhausted—his arms hurt, his back hurt, his legs hurt from all the walking. But it was a good kind of exhaustion. The kind that came from doing something that mattered.\n\nPenny came and sat beside him. She had spent the day testing soil samples, cataloging data, preparing for the planting that would come later.\n\n\"How was your day?\" she asked.\n\n\"I set a stake,\" Oliver said. \"By myself. Well, mostly by myself.\"\n\n\"I saw.\" Penny's head tilted slightly. \"You did well.\"\n\n\"Papa said it was perfect.\"\n\n\"It was. I measured it while you were eating. One point three centimeters off the ideal position. Well within tolerance.\"\n\nOliver laughed. One point three centimeters. On forty hectares, that was nothing.\n\n\"Penny,\" he said, \"do you think we can really do this? Build a house, grow food, make a life out here?\"\n\nPenny was quiet for a moment. When she spoke, her voice was soft.\n\n\"I have been with your mother's family for forty-seven years,\" she said. \"I have seen them fail at things. I have seen them succeed at things. What I have learned is this: the families that succeed are not the ones who never have problems. They are the ones who don't give up when problems come.\"\n\nShe looked out at the dark valley, at the stars beginning to appear overhead.\n\n\"Your family doesn't give up. So yes, Oliver. I think you can do this.\"\n\nOliver nodded. He didn't have anything to say to that. But he felt it, deep in his chest—a warmth that wasn't from the fire.\n\nTomorrow they would start digging the foundation. The day after, they would start building walls. And someday, maybe sooner than he could imagine, they would have a house.\n\nA real house. On their own land. Built with their own hands.\n\nHe couldn't wait.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The House Rises","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The House Rises\n\nDigging the foundation took three days.\n\nThe ground on the ridge was harder than Papa expected. Rocks lay just beneath the surface, some of them as big as Oliver's head. Marchman dug with a heavy shovel, his four arms working in steady rhythm, while Papa and Oliver hauled the dirt away in buckets.\n\nIt was hard work. Harder than anything Oliver had ever done. By the end of each day, his shoulders burned and his hands were blistered. He fell asleep the moment he lay down and woke feeling like he had never rested at all.\n\nBut every morning, when he climbed out of the crawler and looked at the rectangular trench carved into the ridge, he felt something that was stronger than tiredness. Pride, maybe. Or satisfaction. The feeling of watching something grow from nothing.\n\nOn the third day, they finished.\n\nPapa stood at the edge of the trench, looking down at the flat packed earth at the bottom. The foundation was thirty centimeters deep, perfectly level, with drainage channels cut at each corner to carry water away from the house.\n\n\"Not bad,\" Papa said. \"Not bad at all.\"\n\n---\n\nThe wall panels came out of the crawler in flat stacks.\n\nThey were made of a special material—printed in factories in the city, designed to lock together like puzzle pieces. Each panel was light enough for two people to carry, but strong enough to stop wind and rain and keep heat inside.\n\n\"The settlers a hundred years ago had to cut trees and build from wood,\" Papa said, laying out the panels in order. \"We're lucky. These panels will last longer than wood, and they go up faster.\"\n\nMama read the instructions while Papa and Marchman assembled. Oliver's job was to hold panels steady while Papa secured the connectors. Thea's job was to hand tools to whoever needed them and stay out of the way.\n\nThe first wall went up before noon.\n\nOliver stood back and looked at it. It was strange—just one wall, standing alone on the ridge, held up by temporary braces. It didn't look like much. But it was the beginning.\n\n\"Three more to go,\" Papa said. \"Let's keep moving.\"\n\n---\n\nThe walls grew faster than Oliver expected.\n\nOnce they understood the system—how the panels locked together, which connectors went where, what order to do things in—they fell into a rhythm. Papa directed. Marchman lifted. Mama and Penny fitted the smaller pieces. Oliver held things steady and watched and learned.\n\nBy the end of the second day of wall-building, all four walls were up.\n\nThey weren't finished yet—there were no windows, no doors, no roof—but the shape of the house was there. Oliver could walk inside and stand in what would become the kitchen, the main room, the bedrooms. He could see where the windows would go, where the door would open.\n\n\"It's starting to look like something,\" Mama said that evening.\n\nPapa put his arm around her. \"It's starting to look like home.\"\n\n---\n\nThe windows came next.\n\nThey were made of a clear material that was stronger than glass, built to withstand storms and temperature changes. Papa showed Oliver how to fit them into the frames—carefully, slowly, making sure the seals were tight.\n\n\"A window that leaks lets heat out in winter and dust in during storms,\" Papa explained. \"Take your time. Do it right.\"\n\nOliver worked on the window in what would be his and Thea's room. He thought about all the mornings he would look out this window, all the nights he would see the stars through it. He made sure the seals were perfect.\n\nThe door was simpler—a solid panel that swung on hinges, with a latch that locked from inside. Papa hung it himself, adjusting the hinges until it opened and closed smoothly.\n\n\"Try it,\" he told Oliver.\n\nOliver pushed the door open. He stepped through. He was inside the house. Then he stepped back out. He was outside.\n\nSuch a simple thing. But it meant something, having a door. Having an inside and an outside. Having a place that was theirs and a way to close it off from the rest of the world.\n\n---\n\nThe roof was the hardest part.\n\nThe panels had to be lifted high and held in place while the connectors were secured. Even Marchman couldn't do it alone. Everyone worked together—Marchman holding the heavy end, Papa and Mama guiding the lighter end, Oliver standing on a ladder to secure the connectors, Penny calling out adjustments.\n\nIt was slow work. The sun beat down on them. Oliver's arms shook from holding his position on the ladder. Twice they had to stop and start over because a panel wasn't aligned right.\n\nBut finally, finally, the last panel clicked into place.\n\nThey had a roof.\n\nOliver climbed down from the ladder and stood back to look. The house stood on the ridge, solid and complete—walls, windows, door, roof. It was real. It was there.\n\n\"We did it,\" Thea said. \"We really did it.\"\n\n\"Not quite done yet,\" Papa said. \"We need solar panels for power and a water recycler. But yes. The hard part is finished.\"\n\n---\n\nThe solar panels went on the roof, angled to catch the sun.\n\nPenny climbed up and positioned them while Oliver handed panels up one at a time. She connected them to a battery pack inside the house, and suddenly there was power—lights that came on when you touched a switch, outlets where you could charge tools, a small heating unit for cold nights.\n\nThe water recycler was more complicated. Papa had to connect it to the house's plumbing, then run pipes to the cistern they would build outside. For now, they rigged a temporary system—water from the river, filtered and purified, stored in containers inside.\n\n\"Eventually we'll dig a well,\" Papa said. \"And build a proper cistern to catch rainwater. But this will work for now.\"\n\nIt was evening when they finished.\n\nMama made supper in the house's kitchen—the first meal ever cooked there. It was simple food, the same supplies they had been eating for weeks. But it tasted different somehow. Better.\n\nAfter supper, Papa got out his concertina and played.\n\nOliver sat on the floor—they didn't have furniture yet, that would come later—and listened. Through the window, he could see the sun setting over the valley, painting the sky in shades of orange and purple. The music filled the small house, warm and hopeful.\n\nThis was what they had worked for. This was what the journey and the digging and the building had been about. Not just walls and a roof, but a place where a family could be together. A place where music could fill the air and light could shine through windows and a door could close against the night.\n\n---\n\nThat night, they slept in the house for the first time.\n\nTheir beds were just blankets on the floor, but it didn't matter. The floor was solid beneath them. The roof was solid above them. The walls kept out the wind and the dark and everything else.\n\nOliver lay awake for a long time, listening.\n\nThe house made sounds he hadn't expected—small creaks and settles as the panels adjusted to the night air. The wind whispered around the corners. Somewhere outside, an animal called once and fell silent.\n\nBut inside, everything was still. Inside was warm and dry and safe.\n\nHe thought about the city apartment, so far away now. He thought about the journey, the river crossing, the stakes he had driven into the ground. He thought about holding panels steady while Papa secured them, about climbing the ladder to connect roof pieces, about every task he had done to help build this house.\n\nHis hands still hurt. His shoulders still ached. But lying here, in this room, in this house, on this land—it was all worth it.\n\nHe had helped build this.\n\nHe turned over and closed his eyes. Tomorrow there would be more work—furniture to build, a garden to plant, a hundred other tasks they hadn't even thought of yet. But tonight, for the first time since they left the city, Oliver felt like he was exactly where he was supposed to be.\n\nHe fell asleep smiling.\n","narration":null},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"First Planting","file":"chapter-6.md","markdown":"# First Planting\n\n\"Before we plant anything,\" Mama said, \"we need to understand the soil.\"\n\nOliver followed her to the plot they had marked out behind the house. It was a large rectangle—twenty meters by thirty meters—cleared of grass and waiting to become a garden. Papa and Marchman had spent two days removing rocks and breaking up the hard-packed earth. Now the ground was soft and brown and ready.\n\nBut ready for what?\n\n\"Soil isn't just dirt,\" Mama explained, kneeling at the edge of the plot. \"It's alive. Billions of tiny organisms live in every handful, breaking down dead plants and turning them into nutrients. When the soil is healthy, plants grow strong. When it's sick, nothing grows well.\"\n\nShe scooped up a handful of earth and let it fall through her fingers.\n\n\"This soil has been treated by the terraforming crews. They added bacteria and fungi to help plants grow. But every piece of land is different. We need to test it, understand it, learn what it needs.\"\n\n---\n\nPenny brought out the soil testing kit.\n\nIt was a small device about the size of Oliver's hand, with a sharp probe that went into the ground and a screen that showed numbers. Mama showed Oliver how to use it—push the probe in, wait for the beep, read the results.\n\n\"What do the numbers mean?\" Oliver asked.\n\n\"This one is pH—how acidic or alkaline the soil is. Most vegetables like it between six and seven. This soil is six point four. Good.\"\n\nShe pointed to another number.\n\n\"This is nitrogen. Plants need nitrogen to grow leaves. This number should be higher. We'll need to add compost or fertilizer.\"\n\n\"Where do we get compost?\"\n\n\"We make it. All the plant waste—food scraps, dead leaves, anything organic—goes into a pile. Over time, it breaks down into rich soil that we can add to the garden.\"\n\nOliver wrote the numbers in his notebook. pH 6.4. Nitrogen: low. He wasn't sure what all of it meant yet, but he wanted to remember.\n\n---\n\nThey tested the soil in different parts of the plot.\n\nSome areas were better than others. The south side had more nutrients; the north side was sandier and drained faster. Near the edge where the grass used to grow, the soil was darker and richer.\n\n\"This tells us where to plant different things,\" Mama said. \"Tomatoes like rich soil. Carrots prefer sandy soil because it's easier for their roots to push through. Beans actually add nitrogen to the soil, so we can plant them in the low-nitrogen areas.\"\n\nOliver had never thought about gardening this way. In the city, if you wanted vegetables, you went to the market. The food appeared on shelves, clean and packaged, and you didn't have to think about where it came from.\n\nOut here, every vegetable came from the ground, grown by your own hands. And that meant understanding what the ground needed.\n\n---\n\nPenny showed Oliver how to read the soil sensors.\n\nThey were small stakes that stayed in the ground, monitoring conditions constantly and sending data to a tablet. Temperature. Moisture. Nutrient levels. Everything the plants needed, measured every hour.\n\n\"Watch the patterns,\" Penny said, showing him a graph on the tablet. \"See how the moisture drops during the day and rises at night? That's because water evaporates when the sun is out. The plants need consistent moisture, so we water in the morning and evening when evaporation is lowest.\"\n\n\"How do you know all this?\"\n\nPenny's head tilted slightly. \"I was built to help families manage their homes and land. Your grandmother programmed me with gardening knowledge fifty years ago. Some things I learned from her. Some things I learned from watching. Some things I learned from mistakes.\"\n\n\"You make mistakes?\"\n\n\"Every gardener does. The important thing is to learn from them.\" She handed him the tablet. \"This is yours now. Check it every morning and evening. Write down anything unusual. By the end of the season, you'll understand this garden better than anyone.\"\n\nOliver looked at the tablet, at the lines and numbers and graphs. It was like a language he didn't speak yet. But he wanted to learn.\n\n---\n\nThe first planting day was chaotic.\n\nPapa had laid out the beds according to Mama's plan—rows of mounded soil, with paths between them for walking and kneeling. But actually putting seeds in the ground was harder than it looked.\n\n\"Not too deep,\" Mama told Oliver, watching him push bean seeds into the soil. \"Twice the depth of the seed, no more. If they're too deep, they won't have enough energy to reach the surface.\"\n\n\"Like this?\" Oliver showed her.\n\n\"Perfect. Now cover them gently and pat the soil down. Not too hard—they need air around them.\"\n\nNearby, Thea was \"helping\" with the carrot seeds. Carrot seeds were tiny, almost like dust, and Thea kept spilling them.\n\n\"Oops,\" she said, for the fifth time.\n\nMama laughed. \"That's all right. Carrots need to be thinned anyway. A few extra won't hurt.\"\n\n\"What's thinning?\"\n\n\"When the seedlings come up, they'll be too close together. We pull out the weak ones so the strong ones have room to grow.\"\n\n\"That sounds mean.\"\n\n\"It sounds mean, but it's necessary. If we don't thin them, none of them will grow properly. Sometimes taking care of something means making hard choices.\"\n\n---\n\nThey planted for three days.\n\nBeans. Carrots. Tomatoes that started as tiny seedlings Mama had grown in pots during the journey. Squash seeds that were bigger than Oliver's thumbnail. Lettuce and spinach and herbs whose names Oliver kept forgetting.\n\nBy the end, the garden plot was full. Each bed was marked with a stake showing what was planted there. Stakes made by Oliver, just like the stakes he had set for the house.\n\n\"Now what?\" Thea asked.\n\n\"Now we wait,\" Mama said. \"And water. And watch.\"\n\n---\n\nWaiting was harder than planting.\n\nEvery morning, Oliver checked the soil sensors and wrote down the numbers. Every evening, he helped water the beds, carrying buckets from the cistern they had built to catch rainwater. Every day, he looked for any sign of green poking through the brown soil.\n\nFor five days, nothing happened.\n\n\"Is something wrong?\" Oliver asked Mama. \"Should something be growing by now?\"\n\nMama smiled. \"Seeds take time. They're waking up down there, drinking water, sending out roots. You can't see it, but they're working hard. Give them a few more days.\"\n\nOn the seventh day, Oliver saw the first sprout.\n\nIt was a bean plant—a tiny green loop pushing up through the soil, so small he almost missed it. He called for Mama, and they knelt together to look at it.\n\n\"There,\" Mama said softly. \"That's life. That's what we planted.\"\n\nOliver reached out to touch the sprout, then stopped. It looked fragile. He didn't want to hurt it.\n\n\"You can touch it,\" Mama said. \"Gently. Plants are stronger than they look.\"\n\nHe brushed the tiny leaves with his fingertip. They were soft and cool and impossibly delicate. A week ago, this was just a dry seed in a packet. Now it was alive, reaching for the sun, growing.\n\nHe had done this. He and Mama and Papa and Thea. They had put seeds in the ground and made life happen.\n\n---\n\nThe next few weeks, the garden exploded.\n\nNot all at once—different plants grew at different speeds. The beans came up first, then the lettuce. The carrots took forever, and the tomatoes grew slowly at first and then suddenly got tall.\n\nOliver recorded everything in his notebook. Which plants grew fastest. Which ones struggled. When he watered, and how much, and what the sensors showed the next morning. He drew pictures of the seedlings at different stages, trying to capture how they changed.\n\nOne evening, Penny found him sitting by the garden, notebook open, watching the plants.\n\n\"You're becoming a gardener,\" she said.\n\n\"I don't know,\" Oliver said. \"I just like watching them grow. Knowing that we made this happen.\"\n\n\"That's what gardening is. Planting something, caring for it, watching it become more than what you started with.\" Penny's sensor plates lifted slightly. \"Your mother was the same way, when she was your age. She kept notebooks too. Filled them with drawings and numbers and observations.\"\n\n\"Really?\"\n\n\"She kept them for years. I wonder if she still has them somewhere.\"\n\nThat night, Oliver asked Mama about the notebooks.\n\nShe smiled and went to one of the boxes they still hadn't unpacked. She pulled out a stack of small books, worn and faded, held together with a rubber band.\n\n\"I forgot I brought these,\" she said. \"I almost left them behind, but I couldn't.\"\n\nShe handed one to Oliver. Inside, in a child's handwriting, were drawings of plants and numbers and observations. Just like his.\n\n\"Page thirty-two,\" Mama said. \"I wrote about my first bean plant. I was eight years old.\"\n\nOliver turned to page thirty-two. The entry was short:\n\n*The bean came up today!! It has two little leaves. I named it Bernard.*\n\nHe laughed. \"You named it?\"\n\n\"I named all of them that first year. Bernard the bean, Clarence the carrot, Tina the tomato.\" She smiled. \"I was very serious about it.\"\n\nOliver looked at his own notebook, at the careful measurements and drawings. Maybe he would name his plants too. Not out loud, where anyone could hear. But in his notebook, just for himself.\n\nHe turned back to the garden plot, where rows of green were pushing toward the sky.\n\nHis plants. His garden. His work.\n\nGrowing.\n","narration":null},{"id":7,"number":7,"title":"Neighbors","file":"chapter-7.md","markdown":"# Neighbors\n\nOliver saw the crawler first.\n\nHe was checking the garden sensors when a flash of movement caught his eye—something moving on the road that led down from the western hills. He shaded his eyes and squinted.\n\nA crawler. Coming this way.\n\n\"Papa!\" he called. \"Someone's coming!\"\n\nPapa came out of the house, wiping his hands on a rag. He had been building a table—their first real piece of furniture. He looked where Oliver was pointing.\n\n\"Well,\" Papa said slowly. \"Looks like we're not alone anymore.\"\n\n---\n\nThe Okonkwo family arrived at midday.\n\nTheir crawler was newer than the Aldridges'—bigger, with a metal cover instead of canvas. A man drove, with a woman beside him. Oliver could see faces in the windows of the back—children, watching as their parents guided the crawler down into the valley.\n\nOliver hung back as Papa walked out to meet them.\n\nIn the city, meeting new people hadn't mattered much. You passed strangers on the street every day. If you didn't like someone, you just avoided them. There were always other people.\n\nOut here, things were different. These would be their neighbors—probably their only neighbors for a long time. What if Oliver didn't like them? What if they didn't like him?\n\nHe felt his stomach twist.\n\n\"Come on,\" Mama said, putting a hand on his shoulder. \"Let's go say hello.\"\n\n---\n\nThe man's name was Mr. Okonkwo. He was tall and serious-looking, with a deep voice and a firm handshake. The woman was Mrs. Okonkwo, smaller than her husband but with quick eyes that seemed to notice everything.\n\n\"We've been watching your smoke for days,\" Mr. Okonkwo said. \"We knew someone was here. Good to finally meet you.\"\n\n\"How was your journey?\" Papa asked.\n\n\"Long. The river was high—we almost had to wait a week for it to go down. But we made it.\"\n\nThe adults talked about the route, the roads, the weather. Oliver half-listened, but his attention was on the crawler, where the Okonkwo children were climbing out.\n\nThere were three of them. A tall boy, maybe twelve. A girl about Thea's age, with braided hair and a bright dress. And another boy, somewhere between them, who jumped down from the crawler and immediately started looking around.\n\nHe had a restless energy about him—his head turning this way and that, his feet moving even when he was standing still. He spotted Oliver watching and came straight over.\n\n\"I'm Emeka,\" he said. \"We're going to live next door. Well, not next door like in the city. But our land touches yours. My father showed me on the map.\"\n\n\"I'm Oliver.\"\n\n\"Have you been here long? Is it hard? Do you have animals yet? Have you seen any wild ones? My sister said there are animals with four eyes here but I don't believe her. Are there?\"\n\nOliver blinked. Emeka talked fast—faster than anyone Oliver had ever met. Before he could answer one question, there were three more.\n\n\"We've been here about a month,\" Oliver said. \"And I haven't seen any four-eyed animals.\"\n\n\"Ha! I knew she was making it up. What about the river? Is it really as clear as they say? My father said you can see straight to the bottom. Is that true?\"\n\n\"Yes. It's called the Glass River.\"\n\n\"Can we go see it? Right now? I've been sitting in that crawler for so long, I need to move.\"\n\nOliver looked at Mama, who nodded.\n\n\"Go ahead,\" she said. \"But stay where I can see you.\"\n\n---\n\nEmeka didn't stop talking the whole way to the river.\n\nHe talked about the city they had left, which was different from Oliver's city—bigger, older, with a different name. He talked about the journey, and how boring it was, and how his little sister had cried every night for the first week. He talked about his father's plans for their land, and his mother's plans for a garden, and his older brother's plans to catch fish in the river.\n\n\"What are your plans?\" Emeka asked suddenly.\n\nOliver thought about it. \"I don't know. Help my parents, I guess. Learn how things work.\"\n\n\"That's not a plan. That's just... doing whatever you're told.\"\n\n\"Is there something wrong with that?\"\n\nEmeka shrugged. \"I don't know. I just like having my own plans. Things I want to do that aren't about anybody else.\"\n\nThey reached the river. Emeka dropped to his knees and stuck his hand in the water.\n\n\"Cold!\" he said. \"And you're right, you can see everything. Look at those fish! I'm going to catch one. My brother thinks he's going to be the fisherman, but I'm going to catch one first. You'll see.\"\n\nOliver sat on a rock and watched Emeka splash around in the shallows, making so much noise that every fish for a hundred meters probably fled. He couldn't decide if Emeka was annoying or exciting. Maybe both.\n\n---\n\nThat night, both families ate together.\n\nThey set up tables outside, between the two crawlers—the Okonkwos hadn't started building yet, so they were still living in theirs. Mama and Mrs. Okonkwo combined their supplies, and together they made a real meal: fresh bread, rehydrated vegetables, even a sweet pudding that Mrs. Okonkwo had been saving for a special occasion.\n\n\"To new neighbors,\" Papa said, raising his cup.\n\n\"To the eastern valleys,\" Mr. Okonkwo replied.\n\nThey clinked cups and drank.\n\nOliver sat with the Okonkwo children. Emeka's older brother, who was named Samuel, was quiet and serious, like his father. Emeka's younger sister, who was named Ada, immediately attached herself to Thea, and the two of them ran off to look at flowers.\n\n\"Your house looks good,\" Samuel said, nodding toward the building on the ridge. \"How long did it take?\"\n\n\"About two weeks,\" Oliver said. \"My father and Marchman—that's our workerbot—did most of the heavy work. But everyone helped.\"\n\n\"We'll need to start building soon. Before the rainy season.\"\n\n\"There's a rainy season?\"\n\nSamuel looked at him. \"You didn't know? In about six weeks, the rains come. They last for a month, maybe more. If you don't have a roof by then, everything gets wet.\"\n\nOliver hadn't known that. He wondered what else he didn't know about this land.\n\n---\n\nAfter dinner, Emeka grabbed Oliver's arm.\n\n\"Come on,\" he said. \"I want to see where our land meets yours.\"\n\nThey walked west, toward the hills, following the property stakes. The sun was setting, painting the sky in shades of red and gold. The grass rippled in the evening breeze.\n\n\"Here,\" Emeka said, stopping at a stake. \"This is our corner. And that\"—he pointed to another stake, about twenty meters away—\"is yours. Everything in between is the boundary.\"\n\nOliver looked at the line of stakes stretching away into the distance. On one side, his family's land. On the other side, Emeka's.\n\n\"We're neighbors,\" Emeka said. \"Really neighbors. Not like in the city, where there's a wall between you and you never see each other.\"\n\n\"Yeah.\"\n\n\"I'm going to build a path here. From my house to yours. So we can visit whenever we want.\"\n\nOliver smiled. He hadn't thought about that—about being able to walk to a friend's house, any time, without asking permission or scheduling or any of the complicated things that visiting people in the city required.\n\n\"I'd like that,\" he said.\n\nEmeka grinned. \"Good. Because I don't know anybody else out here, and you seem all right. A little quiet, but all right.\"\n\n\"You talk enough for both of us.\"\n\nEmeka laughed—a loud, sudden laugh that echoed across the empty valley. \"That's true. My mother says I could talk the ears off a statue. But that's just how I think, you know? Out loud.\"\n\nOliver didn't know. He did his thinking on the inside, in his notebook, in the quiet moments when no one else was around. But maybe that was okay. Maybe two people didn't have to be the same to be friends.\n\n---\n\nThey walked back as the stars came out.\n\nThe two moons were rising—one pale blue, one amber—casting strange double shadows across the grass. In the distance, Oliver could see the lights of both houses: his family's house on the ridge, and the glow of the Okonkwo crawler below.\n\n\"Tomorrow I'll help you scout for a building site,\" Oliver said. \"I know where the best ground is. Papa and I surveyed the whole area.\"\n\n\"Really? You'd do that?\"\n\n\"Sure. That's what neighbors do, right? Help each other.\"\n\nEmeka nodded slowly. \"In the city, neighbors didn't help each other much. Everybody was too busy, my father said. Too worried about their own problems.\"\n\n\"Maybe it's different out here.\"\n\n\"Maybe.\" Emeka looked at the empty valley, at the two small points of light in the darkness. \"Maybe when there's only a few of you, you have to look out for each other. Because there's no one else to do it.\"\n\nOliver thought about that as they walked. No one else to do it. In the city, there were always other people—police, doctors, repair crews, everyone you needed just a call away. Out here, it was just them.\n\nBut maybe that wasn't scary. Maybe it was just different. Maybe it meant that the people who were here had to matter more to each other.\n\n---\n\nAt the edge of the Okonkwo camp, they said goodnight.\n\n\"See you tomorrow,\" Emeka said. \"We'll find the best building site in the whole valley. And then we'll start on that path.\"\n\n\"See you tomorrow.\"\n\nOliver walked home alone, climbing the ridge in the starlight. When he reached the house, he turned and looked back. He could see Emeka's figure in the distance, climbing into the crawler, a shadow against the glow of lights.\n\nA month ago, he didn't know anyone in the eastern valleys. Now he had a neighbor. Maybe even a friend.\n\nHe went inside, where Mama and Papa were talking quietly by lamplight.\n\n\"Did you have a good time?\" Mama asked.\n\n\"Yeah,\" Oliver said. \"I did.\"\n\nHe went to his room and opened his notebook. At the bottom of the day's entries, he added one more line:\n\n*The Okonkwos arrived today. Emeka talks a lot. I think we might be friends.*\n\nHe closed the notebook and looked out the window at the two moons hanging in the sky. Tomorrow there would be work to do—helping the Okonkwos get started, building that path Emeka had talked about, checking the garden, all the hundred tasks that never seemed to end.\n\nBut tonight, for the first time since they arrived, Oliver didn't feel like the only kid in the world.\n\nThat was worth something. That was worth a lot.\n","narration":null},{"id":8,"number":8,"title":"Mr. Tarrant's Advice","file":"chapter-8.md","markdown":"# Mr. Tarrant's Advice\n\nThe stranger came from the south.\n\nOliver was working in the garden when he heard the sound—not a crawler, but something smaller and lighter. He straightened up and shaded his eyes.\n\nA man was walking across the valley, leading a small cart behind him. The cart was pulled by a four-legged machine that moved smoothly over the grass, not quite walking but not quite rolling either. Oliver had never seen anything like it.\n\nPapa came out of the house. \"Hello there!\" he called.\n\nThe man raised a hand in greeting but didn't hurry. He walked at a steady pace, neither fast nor slow, like someone who knew exactly how long the journey would take and saw no point in rushing.\n\nWhen he reached the house, Oliver could see him clearly. He was old—older than Papa, older than anyone Oliver had met since leaving the city. His face was weathered and lined, his hair gray and thin, his hands rough and scarred from years of work.\n\n\"Name's Tarrant,\" he said. \"I farm about thirty kilometers south of here, in the old valley. Heard there were new families settling in this area. Thought I'd come see how you're getting on.\"\n\n---\n\nMr. Tarrant didn't talk much, but when he did, people listened.\n\nHe walked the property with Papa, looking at everything—the house, the garden, the water system, the tool shed Marchman was building. He didn't compliment anything. He didn't criticize, either. He just looked, and nodded, and occasionally asked a question.\n\n\"How deep did you set your foundation?\"\n\n\"Thirty centimeters.\"\n\n\"That'll do for now. Before winter, add another ten. Ground shifts when it freezes.\"\n\n\"Does it freeze here?\"\n\n\"Sometimes. Not often. But when it does, you'll want those extra centimeters.\"\n\nHe looked at the garden, walking slowly between the rows. He bent down to examine the bean plants, feeling the leaves between his fingers. He dug a small hole near the carrots and looked at the soil.\n\n\"Who's been watering this?\"\n\n\"My son, mostly,\" Papa said. \"Oliver.\"\n\nMr. Tarrant grunted. \"Good job. Even moisture, not too much. Most newcomers overwater.\"\n\nOliver felt a flush of pride. He hadn't even known you could overwater a garden.\n\n---\n\nThat evening, Mr. Tarrant stayed for dinner.\n\nHe sat at the table Papa had built, eating slowly and steadily, not saying much while the food was in front of him. But after dinner, with a cup of tea in his hands, he began to talk.\n\n\"I've been in the eastern valleys for twenty-three years,\" he said. \"Came out when I was younger than you.\" He nodded at Papa. \"Different then. No terraforming crews, no survey stakes. You just found a piece of land and started working.\"\n\n\"What was it like?\" Mama asked.\n\n\"Hard. Lonely. My wife and I lost our first crop to a fungus we'd never seen before. Lost the second crop to drought. Third year, we figured it out. Started keeping records of what worked and what didn't. By the fifth year, we were feeding ourselves and having extra to trade.\"\n\n\"Trade with who?\"\n\n\"Other settlers, at first. Then the supply convoys started coming through. Now there's a market town about sixty kilometers east. You can sell your surplus there and buy things you can't make yourself.\"\n\nOliver listened carefully. He hadn't thought about what would happen after this first year—how they would get the things they couldn't grow or build. It was another piece of the puzzle he hadn't known was missing.\n\n---\n\nAfter dinner, Oliver was clearing dishes when Mr. Tarrant spoke to him directly.\n\n\"You're the one keeping the garden records?\"\n\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\n\"Show me.\"\n\nOliver fetched his notebook from his room. His hands were sweating. He didn't know why—it was just a notebook, just numbers and drawings. But something about Mr. Tarrant made him want to do well.\n\nMr. Tarrant took the notebook and turned through the pages slowly. He looked at the moisture readings, the growth observations, the drawings of seedlings at different stages. He didn't say anything for a long time.\n\n\"How old are you?\" he finally asked.\n\n\"Nine.\"\n\nMr. Tarrant nodded. \"When I was nine, I didn't know enough to keep records. Took me until I was thirty to figure out how important it was.\" He handed the notebook back. \"You keep doing this. Every day, every season, every year. In ten years, you'll know this land better than anyone.\"\n\n\"Really?\"\n\n\"Land has patterns. Weather, soil, plants—they all have patterns. The patterns change slowly, so slow you can't see them in one season or even one year. But if you write it all down, and you look back over years, you start to see things. When the dry spells come. When the wet spells come. Which plants do well and which struggle. That knowledge is worth more than money.\"\n\nOliver looked at his notebook with new eyes. It wasn't just a record of what had happened. It was a way of understanding the future.\n\n---\n\nThe next morning, Mr. Tarrant walked the property again.\n\nThis time, Oliver went with him. The old man moved slowly, stopping often to look at things—a patch of native plants growing near the river, a bird's nest in a low tree, the way the ground sloped near the south boundary.\n\n\"What do you see there?\" he asked Oliver, pointing at the ground.\n\nOliver looked. It was just grass, as far as he could tell. \"Nothing special.\"\n\n\"Look at the color. See how it's darker there?\"\n\nNow that he looked carefully, Oliver could see it—a strip of grass that was slightly darker green than the grass around it.\n\n\"That means water,\" Mr. Tarrant said. \"Underground. Probably an old stream bed that dried up thousands of years ago. The water's still there, just deeper now. If you ever need a well, drill there.\"\n\n\"How do you know that?\"\n\n\"Experience. I've seen it before, in other valleys. The patterns repeat.\"\n\nThey walked on. Mr. Tarrant pointed out other things—a type of bush that grew where the soil was rich, a kind of grass that only appeared in sandy areas, the way animals left trails through the vegetation when they came to drink from the river.\n\n\"The land tells you what it needs,\" Mr. Tarrant said. \"You just have to learn how to listen.\"\n\n---\n\nBefore Mr. Tarrant left, he gave Papa a list.\n\n\"Things you need before winter,\" he said. \"Extra insulation for the house. Backup power cells in case the solar panels get buried in snow. A root cellar for storing vegetables. And talk to the other families—pool your resources, help each other. Nobody survives out here alone.\"\n\n\"Thank you,\" Papa said. \"We appreciate you taking the time.\"\n\n\"Self-interest,\" Mr. Tarrant said. \"More families means more trade. More trade means we all do better.\" He paused. \"Also, it's lonely being the only ones out here. Nice to have neighbors, even if they're thirty kilometers away.\"\n\nHe shook hands with Papa and Mama, nodded to Oliver and Thea, and began walking back the way he had come, the little cart rolling behind him.\n\nOliver watched until he disappeared over the southern hills.\n\n---\n\nThat night, Oliver added a new section to his notebook.\n\n*Things I learned from Mr. Tarrant:*\n\nHe wrote down everything he could remember—about the underground water, the dark grass, the bush that meant rich soil. He wrote about the importance of keeping records, about learning to read the land, about the patterns that only showed themselves over years.\n\nAt the bottom, he added:\n\n*\"You keep records. Good. That's how you learn what works.\"*\n\nHe underlined it twice.\n\nThen he turned to a fresh page and wrote the date at the top. Tomorrow he would add more observations. And the day after that. And the day after that.\n\nIn ten years, Mr. Tarrant had said, he would know this land better than anyone.\n\nOliver was going to make sure that was true.\n","narration":null},{"id":9,"number":9,"title":"The Network","file":"chapter-9.md","markdown":"# The Network\n\nThe Lindgrens arrived at the end of summer.\n\nThey came in a crawler even older than the Aldridges', piled high with belongings and trailing a cloud of dust. There were six of them—Mr. and Mrs. Lindgren, their teenage son Erik, and the twins, Liv and Astrid, who were seven years old and impossible to tell apart.\n\n\"Which one are you?\" Thea asked the twin standing closest to her.\n\n\"I'm Liv,\" the girl said. Then she grinned. \"Or maybe I'm Astrid. Sometimes we switch.\"\n\nThe other twin giggled. Thea's eyes went wide with delight.\n\n\"Uh oh,\" Oliver muttered to Emeka.\n\n\"Double uh oh,\" Emeka agreed.\n\nWithin an hour, the three girls had disappeared into the tall grass along the river, their laughter floating back on the wind. By dinner, they had already hatched three schemes, broken one rule, and started what Thea called a \"secret club\" with a password nobody else was allowed to know.\n\n\"They're going to be trouble,\" Oliver told Mama.\n\nMama smiled. \"Good trouble, I think. Thea needs friends her own age.\"\n\n---\n\nThe Lindgrens weren't the only new family.\n\nIn the weeks that followed, others arrived—the Vasquezes from a mining settlement to the west, the Henrys from a city in the northern hemisphere, the Parkinsons with their grandmother and their baby and their three dogs. One by one, crawlers rolled down into the valley, found their stakes, and began the hard work of building.\n\nThe valley that had been empty was becoming full.\n\nNot full like the city—there were still wide open spaces between the homesteads, still room to walk for an hour without seeing another person. But the empty feeling was gone. At night, Oliver could see lights in the distance—the Okonkwos to the west, the Lindgrens to the northwest, the Vasquezes across the river. Each light meant a family, a kitchen, someone else making a home.\n\nThey weren't alone anymore.\n\n---\n\nThe work days started because there was too much to do.\n\nEvery family needed a house built before the rainy season. Every family needed a garden planted, a well dug, a water system set up. One family working alone could barely keep up. But if everyone worked together—\n\n\"We'll rotate,\" Papa suggested at a gathering of all the families. \"One day, everyone helps the Lindgrens. Next day, everyone helps the Vasquezes. We share tools, share knowledge, share labor. By the time the rains come, everyone will have a roof.\"\n\nThe other adults agreed. Mr. Okonkwo drew up a schedule. Mrs. Parkinson organized the tool sharing. And the next morning, every able body in the valley showed up at the Lindgren site to help raise walls.\n\nOliver worked alongside Emeka and Samuel and Erik Lindgren and half a dozen other kids, hauling panels, holding things steady, passing tools to the adults who knew how to use them. It was hard work, harder than anything he'd done on his own family's house because the sun was hotter now and there were more people to coordinate.\n\nBut it was also... fun?\n\nHe didn't know exactly how to describe it. There was something about working together, about seeing a wall go up that you had helped raise, about knowing that you were part of something bigger than yourself. At the end of the day, when the Lindgren house had four walls and everyone sat down to share a meal, Oliver felt like he belonged to something.\n\nNot just his family. Not just his land.\n\nSomething bigger.\n\n---\n\nOn the rest days, Oliver and Emeka explored.\n\nThey followed the Glass River upstream, past the ford where the Aldridges had crossed, into the hills where the water ran faster over rocks and fallen logs. They found a swimming hole, deep and cold, where the river widened into a natural pool. They found caves in the hillside, small and dark, that Emeka was convinced held treasure.\n\n\"There's nothing in here,\" Oliver said, shining his light into another empty hole.\n\n\"Not yet,\" Emeka said. \"But maybe there will be. Maybe we should hide something, and then in a hundred years, someone will find it and wonder who we were.\"\n\n\"What would we hide?\"\n\nEmeka thought about it. \"Something that tells our story. Like... a letter. Or a map. Or one of your drawings.\"\n\nOliver looked at the empty cave. It wasn't a bad idea, actually. Leaving something behind for people who came after. Proof that they had been here.\n\n\"Maybe when we're older,\" he said. \"When we have something worth leaving.\"\n\n\"Deal,\" Emeka said. He spat on his palm and held out his hand. \"When we're older, we come back here and bury our treasure.\"\n\nOliver spat on his own palm and shook. It was a silly ritual, the kind of thing little kids did. But out here, with no one watching, it felt right.\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, Thea and the twins were getting into everything.\n\nThey built a fort in the grass between the Aldridge and Lindgren properties—a tangled mess of sticks and stolen canvas that collapsed every time the wind blew. They tried to catch fish in the river using nets made from Mama's old stockings. They climbed trees they shouldn't climb, explored gullies they shouldn't explore, and once came home covered in mud from head to toe with no explanation for how it had happened.\n\n\"We were investigating,\" Liv said solemnly.\n\n\"It was scientific,\" Astrid added.\n\n\"We found important things,\" Thea concluded.\n\nNo one could get them to say what the important things were. Oliver suspected they had just fallen in a puddle and made up the rest.\n\nBut he understood, in a way. They were learning the land too, just in their own way. Running and climbing and getting dirty was how kids their age figured things out. By the time they were Oliver's age, they would know every hiding spot in the valley.\n\n---\n\nThe idea for the common house came from Mrs. Henry.\n\n\"We need a place to gather,\" she said at one of the evening meetings that had become a regular thing. \"Somewhere big enough for all of us. For meetings, for celebrations, for bad weather when we can't be outside.\"\n\n\"We barely have enough materials for our own houses,\" Mr. Vasquez pointed out.\n\n\"We pool what we have left over. Everyone contributes what they can. It doesn't have to be fancy—just four walls and a roof and enough room for all the families to fit inside.\"\n\nThe adults talked it over. There were practical concerns—where to build, how to share the work, who would maintain it once it was finished. But underneath the practical talk, Oliver could feel the excitement.\n\nThis wasn't just about having a building. It was about being something more than separate families living near each other. It was about being a community.\n\n---\n\nThey built the common house on a rise at the center of the valley.\n\nIt was bigger than any of the family homes—twice as wide, with high ceilings and windows on all sides. The families worked on it together, fitting the work around their own tasks, contributing whatever time and materials they could spare.\n\nOliver helped with the interior walls. He was good at the detail work now—fitting panels precisely, making sure seals were tight, checking measurements twice before cutting anything. Emeka teased him about being slow, but Oliver noticed that Emeka's sections always had to be redone while Oliver's passed inspection the first time.\n\n\"Careful is faster than fixing mistakes,\" Oliver told him.\n\n\"You sound like my father,\" Emeka groaned.\n\n\"Your father is smart.\"\n\n---\n\nThe common house was finished on a day in late summer.\n\nAll the families gathered to see it—fourteen adults, eleven children, three workerbots, and assorted utility robots including Penny. They stood in a loose circle around the building, looking at what they had made together.\n\n\"It's beautiful,\" Mama said quietly.\n\nIt wasn't beautiful, not really. It was plain and practical, built for function rather than appearance. But there was something beautiful about what it represented. All these people, strangers a few months ago, coming together to build something none of them could have built alone.\n\nPapa stepped forward. \"I think we should name it,\" he said. \"Every important place needs a name.\"\n\n\"The Meeting Hall,\" someone suggested.\n\n\"The Gathering Place.\"\n\n\"The Big House.\"\n\n\"What about Valley House?\" Oliver said. Everyone looked at him. He felt his face get hot. \"Because... it's in the valley. And it belongs to everyone in the valley.\"\n\nThere was a moment of silence. Then Mr. Okonkwo nodded slowly.\n\n\"Valley House,\" he said. \"I like it.\"\n\nOthers murmured agreement. And just like that, the building had a name.\n\n---\n\nThat night, they held the first gathering in Valley House.\n\nSomeone had strung lights from the ceiling. Someone else had carried in tables and chairs. The room was full of people and noise and warmth—Emeka arguing with his brother, the twins chasing each other around the tables, adults laughing and talking and passing food.\n\nOliver stood by the door for a moment, watching.\n\nA few months ago, his family had been the only people in the eastern valleys. They had arrived at empty land, with nothing but stakes in the ground and the hope that they could build a life here.\n\nNow look at them.\n\nHouses dotted the valley. Gardens grew behind every home. Children ran through the grass, and lights glowed in windows, and people gathered in a building they had made together.\n\nThis wasn't just their land anymore. It was becoming something bigger.\n\nIt was becoming a town.\n\nOliver smiled and went to join his family. Emeka waved him over to a corner where the kids were planning some kind of expedition for tomorrow. Thea ran past with the twins close behind, all three of them laughing.\n\nOutside, the two moons rose over the eastern valleys, shining down on all of it—the houses and the gardens and the Valley House and the people inside.\n\nHome, Oliver thought.\n\nNot just their home.\n\nEveryone's home.\n","narration":null},{"id":10,"number":10,"title":"When Things Go Wrong","file":"chapter-10.md","markdown":"# When Things Go Wrong\n\nThe storm came without warning.\n\nOne moment, the sky was clear. The next, dark clouds were boiling over the western hills, moving faster than Oliver had ever seen clouds move. The wind picked up, turning warm and restless, making the grass flatten and the trees bend.\n\n\"Everyone inside,\" Papa said, his voice tight. \"Now.\"\n\nThey barely made it to the house before the rain started.\n\nIt wasn't normal rain. It came down in sheets, so thick Oliver couldn't see the garden from the window. The wind howled around the corners of the house, finding every crack and gap. Thea pressed close to Mama, her eyes wide.\n\n\"It's just a storm,\" Mama said. But her voice was strained.\n\nPapa was at the window, staring out at the gray blur. \"The garden,\" he said quietly. \"The tomatoes aren't staked well enough. The beans are just starting to climb.\"\n\nOliver understood. They had spent months building this garden, planting seeds, watching them grow. If the storm flattened everything, they would have to start over—but the planting season was almost over. There might not be enough time.\n\n\"Can we do anything?\" Oliver asked.\n\nPapa shook his head. \"Not in this. We wait.\"\n\n---\n\nThe storm lasted three hours.\n\nThe rain hammered the roof. The wind screamed. Once, something crashed outside—later they would find that the tool shed had lost part of its roof. But inside, all they could do was sit and listen and hope.\n\nWhen the rain finally slowed to a drizzle, Papa grabbed his coat.\n\n\"I'm going to check the damage.\"\n\n\"I'll come,\" Oliver said.\n\nPapa looked at him for a moment, then nodded.\n\n---\n\nThe garden was a disaster.\n\nThe tomato plants, which had been waist-high that morning, were bent and broken. The bean stakes had collapsed, tangling the vines in the mud. The lettuce bed was flooded, the leaves battered and torn. Everywhere Oliver looked, he saw damage.\n\n\"We'll lose some of it,\" Papa said heavily. \"Maybe a lot of it.\"\n\nOliver felt his stomach drop. All that work. All those weeks of watering and weeding and watching and waiting. Gone in three hours.\n\nBut Papa was already moving. \"We can save some,\" he said. \"If we work fast. Get the others.\"\n\n---\n\nThe word spread through the valley like fire.\n\nWithin an hour, everyone who could work was in the Aldridge garden. Not just Papa and Oliver—Mr. Okonkwo and Samuel, the Lindgrens, the Vasquezes, even Mrs. Parkinson with her bad knee and her gardening gloves.\n\n\"Tell us what to do,\" Mr. Okonkwo said.\n\nPapa organized them into teams. One group would restake the tomatoes, carefully lifting the broken plants and tying them to new supports. Another group would drain the flooded beds, digging channels to carry the water away. A third group would cover the most damaged plants with protective cloth, giving them a chance to recover.\n\nOliver was put on the drainage team.\n\nIt was hard work. The ground was thick mud, heavy and clinging. Every shovelful felt like it weighed a hundred kilograms. The drizzle kept falling, soaking through Oliver's coat, running down his face. His arms burned. His back ached.\n\nBut he kept digging.\n\n---\n\nNight fell, and they kept working.\n\nSomeone brought lanterns. Someone else brought hot soup and bread from Valley House, passing it around so people could eat without stopping. The children who were too young to help watched from the edges, holding umbrellas over the workers, bringing tools when asked.\n\nMarchman worked without rest.\n\nHe moved through the garden like a machine—which, Oliver reminded himself, he was. His four arms never stopped. He lifted, dug, carried, held things steady, did whatever needed doing. Water streamed off his metal body. His joints creaked and groaned. But he didn't slow down.\n\nOliver found himself working beside him for a while, passing tools, holding things steady while Marchman secured them. The workerbot didn't speak—he rarely did—but once, when Oliver stumbled in the mud, one of those big metal hands caught his arm and steadied him.\n\n\"Thanks,\" Oliver said.\n\nMarchman nodded once and kept working.\n\n---\n\nIt was past midnight when they finally stopped.\n\nEveryone was exhausted. Covered in mud, soaked through, hands blistered and raw. But looking at the garden, Oliver could see that they had saved more than he had expected.\n\nThe tomatoes were upright again, supported by new stakes and careful ties. The beans had been untangled and replanted where they could climb. The flooded beds had been drained, the damaged plants covered with protective cloth.\n\nSome things were lost. A section of lettuce that had been crushed beyond saving. Half the squash plants, their stems snapped at the base. The herbs near the fence, which had been swept away when a small flood channel had overflowed.\n\nBut most of the garden had survived. Most of what they had worked for was still there.\n\n---\n\nPapa found Oliver sitting on an overturned bucket, staring at the garden.\n\nThe sky was clearing. One of the moons was visible through the thinning clouds, casting pale light over the muddy rows.\n\nPapa sat down beside him. He didn't say anything for a long moment.\n\nThen he put his hand on Oliver's shoulder.\n\n\"You did good work tonight,\" he said.\n\nOliver looked at his father. Papa's face was tired, lined, older than Oliver had ever seen it. But there was something else in his expression too. Pride, maybe. Respect.\n\n\"I just dug trenches,\" Oliver said.\n\n\"You worked as hard as anyone here. Harder than some of the adults. You didn't complain, didn't slow down, didn't ask to stop. You just kept going.\"\n\n\"I wanted to help.\"\n\n\"You did help. You're part of this now—not because you're a kid living with your family, but because you earned your place. Tonight, you worked like a grownup. That matters.\"\n\nOliver didn't know what to say. He felt something swelling in his chest, something bigger than he had words for. It wasn't just pride. It was... belonging. Being part of something. Knowing that he mattered.\n\n\"Thanks,\" he finally said.\n\nPapa squeezed his shoulder. \"Let's go get some sleep. Tomorrow there's more work to do.\"\n\n---\n\nThe next day, the whole valley gathered to help.\n\nNot just the Aldridges—every family's garden had taken damage. So they went from homestead to homestead, just like they had done when building houses, working together to repair what the storm had broken.\n\nIt was hard to see the losses. The Okonkwos had lost most of their corn. The Lindgrens' root vegetables were ruined, drowned in their beds. The Vasquezes had a flooded cellar that took three days to drain.\n\nBut the losses could have been so much worse.\n\n\"We built these houses strong,\" Mama said, looking around the valley at the homes that had all survived intact. \"And we planted our gardens together, on good ground with good drainage. If we hadn't worked so hard—if we'd cut corners, taken shortcuts—this storm would have destroyed us.\"\n\n---\n\nThat evening, the families gathered in Valley House.\n\nNot to celebrate—there wasn't much to celebrate, with so much damage to repair. But to be together. To share food and warmth and the simple comfort of not being alone.\n\nMr. Tarrant came too. He had ridden through the storm to check on the new settlers, and now he sat in the corner, his weathered face thoughtful.\n\n\"First bad storm?\" he asked Papa.\n\n\"First one like that.\"\n\n\"There'll be more. The weather here is unpredictable—always has been. But you handled it well. Better than most newcomers.\"\n\n\"We almost lost everything.\"\n\n\"Almost doesn't count. You had a plan, you worked together, you saved what could be saved.\" Mr. Tarrant looked around the room at all the tired, muddy, determined faces. \"That's what matters. Not avoiding problems—nobody can avoid problems. What matters is what you do when problems come.\"\n\n---\n\nLater, Oliver wrote in his notebook.\n\n*The storm came. We lost some plants. We saved more. Everyone helped.*\n\nHe thought for a moment, then added:\n\n*Papa said I did good work. He said I earned my place.*\n\nHe closed the notebook and looked out the window at the recovering garden. Some of the plants were wilted, struggling to recover. Others were already standing straighter, reaching for the light.\n\nIt would take weeks to know how much they had really lost. Weeks of watching and waiting and hoping. But the garden was still there. The house was still there. The community was still there.\n\nThey had been tested, and they had survived.\n\nThat had to count for something.\n\nOliver turned off his lamp and went to sleep. Tomorrow, there would be more work. There was always more work.\n\nBut that was okay. Work was how you built things that lasted.\n\nAnd he was ready.\n","narration":null},{"id":11,"number":11,"title":"The Harvest","file":"chapter-11.md","markdown":"# The Harvest\n\nThe tomatoes ripened on a morning in late autumn.\n\nOliver found them when he went to check the garden, as he did every morning. The plants were heavy with fruit now—green tomatoes turning to orange, orange turning to red. And there, on the highest vine, were three tomatoes that had finally reached the deep, perfect red that meant they were ready.\n\nHe picked them carefully, cradling them in his hands. They were warm from the sun, smooth and heavy. He brought them inside and set them on the kitchen table.\n\nMama looked at them for a long moment. Then she smiled.\n\n\"Our first harvest,\" she said.\n\n---\n\nAfter that, the harvesting didn't stop.\n\nEvery day brought something new. Beans came down from their vines, filling baskets and buckets. Carrots emerged from the earth, orange and sweet. Squash grew fat on their stems, yellow and green and striped. The lettuce they had planted after the storm was finally ready, crisp and tender.\n\nOliver worked in the garden every morning and evening, picking what was ripe, checking what was almost ready, recording everything in his notebook. His hands were stained green and brown from the work. His back ached from bending. But every time he carried a full basket into the house, he felt a satisfaction deeper than anything he had felt before.\n\nThis food had come from the ground—ground he had prepared, seeds he had planted, plants he had watered and weeded and cared for. Every vegetable was proof that they had done something real. That they had made something from nothing.\n\n---\n\nThe other families were harvesting too.\n\nOliver walked with Emeka to the Okonkwo garden one afternoon and found the whole family picking beans. Even little Ada was helping, carrying a small basket that kept getting too heavy for her.\n\n\"Look at this,\" Emeka said, holding up a bean pod as long as his hand. \"We didn't think they'd grow after the storm. But they came back bigger than before.\"\n\n\"Plants are tough,\" Oliver said. \"Penny told me that. They can recover from a lot, as long as the roots are healthy.\"\n\n\"My father says we'll have enough to save some for next year's planting. And enough to trade at the market.\"\n\nThe market—Oliver had almost forgotten about it. Mr. Tarrant had mentioned it months ago, but it had seemed so far away then. Now it was real. They would take their extra vegetables to a town sixty kilometers east and trade them for things they couldn't grow or make.\n\nThey were becoming real farmers.\n\n---\n\nMama preserved everything she could.\n\nShe had learned from Penny years ago how to dry vegetables, pickle them, store them in ways that would keep through the winter. Now she taught Oliver and Thea, working in the kitchen with jars and salt and the big drying racks that Papa had built.\n\n\"Tomatoes go in jars,\" Mama explained, showing Oliver how to pack them tight. \"Covered with oil, sealed properly, they'll last until spring. Beans we dry—spread them out on the racks and let the air do the work. Carrots and squash go in the root cellar, where it's cool and dark.\"\n\n\"Why do we have to save so much?\" Thea asked. \"We can just grow more next year.\"\n\n\"Next year's planting doesn't happen until spring. That's five months away. And we don't know what next year's weather will be like. Maybe there will be drought, or another storm, or something we haven't even imagined. If we save enough now, we'll be safe no matter what comes.\"\n\nOliver understood. It was like what Mr. Tarrant had said about keeping records—the future was uncertain, and the way you prepared for it was by being careful and thorough now.\n\n---\n\nWhen the last vegetables had been picked and the garden stood empty for winter, the families gathered at Valley House to celebrate.\n\nIt wasn't just a dinner. It was a feast.\n\nEvery family brought their best dishes, made from food they had grown themselves. Mrs. Okonkwo made a bean stew with herbs from her garden. Mrs. Lindgren baked bread from wheat they had traded for at the market. The Vasquezes brought roasted squash with honey. The Henrys made a salad of greens so fresh they had been picked that morning.\n\nAnd Mama brought tomatoes—those same tomatoes Oliver had harvested weeks ago, now cooked into a rich red sauce that covered pasta Mr. Tarrant had brought from his own stores.\n\n\"This is amazing,\" Emeka said, his mouth full. \"I could eat this forever.\"\n\nOliver nodded, but he wasn't really listening. He was looking around the room—at the long tables covered with food, at the families laughing and talking, at the lanterns casting warm light over everything.\n\nThis was real. This was happening.\n\nSix months ago, they had arrived in an empty valley with nothing but a crawler full of supplies and the hope that they could build a life here. Now look at them. Houses stood on the ridges. Gardens lay fallow for winter, ready to be planted again in spring. Children played together like they had known each other all their lives.\n\nThey had done it. They had really done it.\n\n---\n\nAfter dinner, the music started.\n\nPapa got out his concertina, and Mr. Lindgren surprised everyone by producing a violin he had kept hidden in his crawler. Mrs. Parkinson, it turned out, could sing—not beautifully, but with enough enthusiasm that everyone joined in.\n\nThe songs were old ones, songs from Earth, songs that had been carried across space by settlers generations ago. Oliver didn't know all the words, but he hummed along, watching the adults dance and the children run in circles and the robots stand patiently in the corners, part of the celebration in their own way.\n\nPenny caught his eye and tilted her head—that gesture that meant she was pleased.\n\n\"Happy?\" she asked.\n\n\"Yeah,\" Oliver said. \"I think so.\"\n\n\"Good. You worked hard for this. You should enjoy it.\"\n\n---\n\nLater, when the music had stopped and people were saying goodnight, Oliver walked outside.\n\nThe night was cold and clear. Both moons were high, the blue one and the amber one, casting double shadows across the valley. He could see the lights of the other houses—the Okonkwos, the Lindgrens, all the families going home after the celebration.\n\nHe stood there for a long time, just looking.\n\nThe house on the ridge behind him—he had helped build that. The garden, lying quiet in the moonlight—he had planted those seeds, watered those plants, saved them from the storm. The community gathering in Valley House—he had been part of that too, part of building it, part of making it matter.\n\nThis was home now.\n\nNot the city. Not the apartment where he had lived for nine years. Not anywhere he had been before.\n\nHere. This valley. This land. These people.\n\nHome.\n\n---\n\nPapa found him outside.\n\n\"Cold night,\" Papa said.\n\n\"I know. I just... wanted to look.\"\n\nPapa nodded. He stood beside Oliver, looking out at the same view—the dark valley, the silver river, the scattered lights of the settlement.\n\n\"Do you remember what I told you, the morning we left the city?\" Papa asked.\n\nOliver thought back. It felt like a lifetime ago. \"You said hard isn't the same as bad.\"\n\n\"That's right. And you know what? It's been hard. Harder than I expected, some days. But looking at this...\" Papa gestured at the valley, at everything they had built. \"I wouldn't trade it for anything.\"\n\n\"Me neither,\" Oliver said.\n\nThey stood together in the cold, father and son, looking at the home they had made.\n\nAfter a while, Mama called them inside. There was hot tea and warm blankets and the comfortable smallness of their own house, the house they had built together, the house that held everything they needed.\n\nOliver went to sleep that night feeling something he hadn't felt since they left the city.\n\nComplete.\n\nLike all the pieces of his life had finally come together, and everything was exactly where it was supposed to be.\n\nOutside, the moons traced their slow arcs across the sky. The valley slept. And spring, with all its new beginnings, was only a few months away.\n","narration":null},{"id":12,"number":12,"title":"Forty Hectares","file":"chapter-12.md","markdown":"# Forty Hectares\n\nSpring came slowly to the eastern valleys.\n\nFirst the days grew longer, the sun climbing higher each morning. Then the snow that had dusted the hills began to melt, trickling down into streams that fed the Glass River. The grass turned from brown to pale green, and small flowers appeared in the meadows—purple and yellow and white, pushing up through the cold soil toward the light.\n\nOliver stood at the window of his room—his real room now, with a proper bed and a desk Papa had built and shelves for his books and notebooks—and watched the valley wake up.\n\nOne year. It had been one year since the letter came.\n\n---\n\nThe garden was ready for planting.\n\nOliver and Mama had spent the winter planning—which crops to grow, where to plant them, how to rotate the beds so the soil stayed healthy. They had seeds saved from last year's harvest, plus new varieties they had traded for at the winter market.\n\n\"This year we'll try wheat,\" Mama said, showing him the small bag of seeds. \"Just a test plot. If it grows well, we can expand next year.\"\n\n\"And fruit trees,\" Papa added. He had brought back three tiny saplings from a nursery Mr. Tarrant knew about—apple, pear, and something called a starfruit that only grew on this planet. \"They won't bear fruit for a few years. But by the time you're grown, they'll be as tall as the house.\"\n\nOliver tried to imagine it—trees as tall as the house, heavy with fruit. It was hard to picture. But then, a year ago, it had been hard to picture any of this.\n\n---\n\nThe new families arrived in early spring.\n\nOliver heard the first crawler coming from miles away—the distant hum of an engine, the crunch of wheels on the road that the settlers had built last autumn, connecting all the homesteads to each other and to the river crossing.\n\n\"Someone's coming,\" he called.\n\nEveryone came out to watch. The crawler rolled down into the valley, dusty and dented from a long journey. A man and woman sat in front, and Oliver could see children peering through the canvas at the back.\n\n\"They look scared,\" Emeka said, coming to stand beside him.\n\n\"We probably looked the same way when we got here.\"\n\n\"I wasn't scared,\" Emeka said. Then, more quietly, \"Okay, maybe a little scared.\"\n\nThe crawler stopped, and the family climbed out. The man looked around at the houses, the gardens being prepared for planting, the people gathered to greet them. His face had the same expression Oliver remembered from his own arrival—overwhelmed, uncertain, wondering if this had been a mistake.\n\nPapa walked forward to shake the man's hand.\n\n\"Welcome to the eastern valleys,\" Papa said. \"I'm Henry Aldridge. We've been expecting you.\"\n\n---\n\nThe newcomers' name was Chen—Mr. and Mrs. Chen, with three children: a boy about Oliver's age, a younger girl, and a baby in Mrs. Chen's arms.\n\nOliver was assigned to show the boy around.\n\nHis name was David. He was quiet, even quieter than Oliver, and he spent the first hour looking at everything without saying much. Oliver remembered that feeling too—trying to take in so much newness that words felt pointless.\n\n\"This is the river,\" Oliver said, leading David down the path he and Emeka had worn over dozens of trips. \"It's called the Glass River because you can see all the way to the bottom. The ford is about two kilometers upstream—that's probably where you crossed.\"\n\nDavid nodded.\n\n\"There's a swimming hole up that way, in the hills. When summer comes, all the kids go there. And caves—Emeka and I found caves. They're empty, but we're going to bury treasure in one someday.\"\n\n\"Treasure?\"\n\n\"Something to leave behind. So people in the future know we were here.\"\n\nDavid thought about this. \"That's a good idea.\"\n\nThey walked along the river in silence for a while. Finally, David spoke again.\n\n\"Is it hard? Living here?\"\n\nOliver considered the question.\n\n\"Yes,\" he said honestly. \"It's hard work. Every day, there's something that needs doing. Building, planting, fixing, carrying. You get tired. Your hands hurt. Sometimes things go wrong and you have to start over.\"\n\nDavid's face fell.\n\n\"But,\" Oliver continued, \"it's also... I don't know how to explain it. In the city, I never felt like I was part of anything. I just went to school and came home and did whatever I was told. Out here, everything I do matters. When I plant a seed, it grows into food. When I build something, it stays built. When I help someone, they help me back.\" He paused. \"It's hard, but it's worth it. Does that make sense?\"\n\nDavid looked out at the valley—the houses on the ridges, the gardens being prepared, the people moving around doing the work of spring.\n\n\"I think so,\" he said. \"I hope so.\"\n\n---\n\nThat evening, the families gathered at Valley House to welcome the Chens.\n\nIt was just like the feast after the harvest, except now there were more people, more food, more noise. The twins had taught the Chen girl some kind of clapping game, and the sound of their laughter echoed off the rafters. The adults talked about crops and weather and all the plans for the coming year.\n\nOliver sat with Emeka and David, teaching David the names of everyone in the settlement.\n\n\"That's Mr. Tarrant—he's not really from here, but he comes by a lot. He knows everything about farming. And that's Samuel—Emeka's brother—he's going to apprentice with the repair crew at the market town next year. And those are the twins, Liv and Astrid, but don't bother trying to tell them apart because they switch on purpose...\"\n\nDavid listened, eyes wide, trying to absorb it all.\n\n\"You'll learn,\" Emeka assured him. \"It took me a while too. But eventually, everyone just feels like family.\"\n\n---\n\nLater, after the gathering broke up and the families headed home, Oliver walked to the edge of the property.\n\nHe did this sometimes, when he needed to think. The western boundary, where the land rose toward the hills, had the best view of the whole valley. From here, you could see everything—the river, the houses, the gardens, Valley House in the center, the road winding away toward the ford.\n\nHe sat on a rock and reached into his pocket.\n\nThe stone was still there. The first one he had collected, on that first night of the journey, when they had camped beside a stream and he had seen more stars than he had ever imagined existed.\n\nHe turned it over in his fingers. Smooth gray, worn by water, warmed by his hand. Such a small thing. But it held everything—the whole journey, the whole year, everything that had happened since that night.\n\nHe thought about the boy he had been then. Nine years old, scared, unable to imagine what forty hectares even looked like.\n\nNow he was ten. Still young, still learning. But different. Stronger. More capable. Someone who had built a house and planted a garden and weathered a storm and helped new settlers find their way.\n\nHe looked out at the valley—at the lights coming on in windows, at the moons rising over the eastern hills, at the land that had become so familiar he could walk it in his sleep.\n\nForty hectares.\n\nA year ago, it had seemed impossibly big. Too much to understand, too much to imagine.\n\nNow it felt exactly right.\n\nEvery field had a name. Every neighbor was a friend. Every path was one he had walked before. The land wasn't a stranger anymore—it was home.\n\n---\n\nPapa found him there, sitting on the rock with the stone in his hand.\n\n\"Room for one more?\" Papa asked.\n\nOliver scooted over. Papa sat down beside him, looking out at the same view.\n\n\"Thinking about something?\" Papa asked.\n\n\"Just... everything. The year. How much has changed.\"\n\nPapa nodded slowly. \"It has changed, hasn't it? Feels like we just got here. But also feels like we've been here forever.\"\n\n\"Next year will be even bigger,\" Oliver said. \"More families coming. More houses. Mr. Tarrant says they might build a school.\"\n\n\"A school would be good. Thea's getting too wild running around with those twins. She needs something to focus on.\"\n\nThey sat in comfortable silence for a while. The moons rose higher. The lights in the valley windows glowed warm and steady.\n\n\"Papa?\" Oliver said.\n\n\"Yeah?\"\n\n\"Thank you. For bringing us here. For... everything.\"\n\nPapa put his arm around Oliver's shoulders.\n\n\"Thank you,\" Papa said. \"For being part of it. For working hard. For becoming who you're becoming.\" He paused. \"I'm proud of you, Oliver. Really proud.\"\n\nOliver didn't say anything. He didn't need to. He just leaned into his father's arm and watched the moons rise over their valley, their home, their forty hectares.\n\nSomewhere in the distance, an animal called—one of the native creatures, the ones with four eyes that the twins were still trying to find. The wind stirred the grass. The stars came out, thousands of them, just like that first night on the road.\n\nA year ago, everything had been new and frightening and impossible.\n\nNow it was just... home.\n\nAnd that, Oliver thought, was exactly how it was supposed to be.\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":12,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
